1
00:00:00,790 --> 00:00:28,501
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:29,207 --> 00:00:33,231
Homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:37,295 --> 00:00:40,018
There are different traditions for chanting.

4
00:00:43,320 --> 00:00:46,685
Next time I'll shut up and just let you get on with it.

5
00:00:52,189 --> 00:00:55,552
I just thought I would take the life of the Buddha and...

6
00:00:56,697 --> 00:01:02,222
mosey on around it and just see what thoughts arise when we contemplate the life.

7
00:01:04,704 --> 00:01:10,010
I suppose there are two things that the Buddha stands for for us.

8
00:01:10,631 --> 00:01:16,016
He's both an exemplar and an archetype.

9
00:01:16,036 --> 00:01:17,878
I've got a definition here of archetype.

10
00:01:18,197 --> 00:01:21,822
It's a primitive mental image in the collective unconscious.

11
00:01:22,402 --> 00:01:23,763
I think that's very young, isn't it?

12
00:01:24,665 --> 00:01:26,046
And a recurrent symbol of

13
00:01:26,227 --> 00:01:28,010
or motif in mythology.

14
00:01:30,453 --> 00:01:48,540
I'm sure that's what it means but I suppose what I mean by it is some sort of template, some sort of inner image which we have really already within ourselves and which the tradition

15
00:01:50,090 --> 00:02:05,052
defines for us in specific ways so that the specific actions that the Buddha takes during his life becomes for us examples of how we ought to behave.

16
00:02:08,617 --> 00:02:17,271
That sort of thing, exemplar and archetype, really exists in all walks of life, doesn't it?

17
00:02:17,312 --> 00:02:18,813
We have an image of the artist

18
00:02:19,991 --> 00:02:24,076
of the academic, of the worker, and so on.

19
00:02:24,837 --> 00:02:29,723
So these sorts of background blueprints exist in our minds anyway.

20
00:02:31,006 --> 00:02:42,760
And spiritually speaking, we have these great figures which remain for us, exemplars and archetypes of our spiritual lives, you see.

21
00:02:43,421 --> 00:02:43,502
Hmm?

22
00:02:45,727 --> 00:03:02,370
One of the interesting questions which arose really from the way the West discovered the Buddha is that there was a time when they didn't actually think he was a human being.

23
00:03:03,230 --> 00:03:11,581
He was a solar deity and the nimbus that was around his head symbolized this origin of being a solar deity.

24
00:03:12,776 --> 00:03:23,889
And the reason I bring it up is because if the teaching had come from a solar deity, how would we feel about that?

25
00:03:25,312 --> 00:03:29,456
It had been channeled down to Ananda and he wrote it all down.

26
00:03:31,778 --> 00:03:40,810
And what the solar deity is saying is that there's a place where there's no suffering and that he's got there and he's got the t-shirts

27
00:03:41,330 --> 00:03:45,776
and it's possible for everybody to make the same place.

28
00:03:47,457 --> 00:03:53,205
But the fact that it's a solar deity does raise a question in the mind, doesn't it?

29
00:03:54,026 --> 00:04:03,759
For instance, if you knew that a deva or some great angel being had climbed Mount Everest,

30
00:04:04,312 --> 00:04:11,600
And so you knew it was possible by certain beings, but you weren't absolutely certain that the human being could actually make the top.

31
00:04:12,662 --> 00:04:17,846
The fact that one person did actually make the top makes it open to everybody.

32
00:04:18,608 --> 00:04:20,829
And everybody can make it, if they want to, that is.

33
00:04:21,750 --> 00:04:28,997
And I remember some time ago, a 70-year-old woman climbed up there.

34
00:04:29,619 --> 00:04:33,442
So it just shows that once somebody has actually...

35
00:04:33,894 --> 00:05:02,906
done something in our history it makes it open to everybody another example of that would be Einstein's theory of relativity so there was a time if I remember rightly when Rutherford who was a scientist I think in Britain said there were only two people who understood relativity Einstein and himself now it seems to be first degree stuff at universities

36
00:05:04,456 --> 00:05:17,612
Unfortunately, the image stops there because even though the Buddha did make it, it doesn't particularly make it that much easier for us that there's been 2,500 years of history of people trying to climb this particular spiritual mountain.

37
00:05:17,913 --> 00:05:28,788
However, it does make it tangible that another human being actually achieved a state of non-suffering.

38
00:05:28,807 --> 00:05:29,569
And...

39
00:05:30,915 --> 00:05:37,425
That should give us that inner confidence that we have all the same potential.

40
00:05:37,504 --> 00:05:43,913
There's no difference in terms of our faculties and being from the Buddha himself.

41
00:05:44,375 --> 00:05:46,617
And that is simply a matter of time.

42
00:05:47,660 --> 00:05:48,600
And we'll get there.

43
00:05:49,461 --> 00:05:52,425
So that should lift our hearts a bit, I hope.

44
00:05:52,646 --> 00:05:56,552
Even in the worst moments of our meditation, when we seem to be

45
00:05:57,139 --> 00:06:23,838
wallowing in hell we should remember that there is always that potential and it lies within us and hell after all is transient so this idea of the Buddha being an archetype and an exemplar is something that we begin to internalize and

46
00:06:25,776 --> 00:06:34,730
It's not really important, so this is another question that often arises as to whether it's historically true, the stories around the Buddha are historically true.

47
00:06:37,233 --> 00:06:52,036
So the only thing that we can say with, I think, absolute certainty is that there was a person called Gautama who lived approximately 2,500 years ago, lived a life and then died and left the teaching behind.

48
00:06:53,130 --> 00:07:08,812
The bare bones of the story, how he was born and how he left home and all that, probably has a basic truth around it, but the stories that are built up around it are, shall we say, apocryphal.

49
00:07:10,896 --> 00:07:21,230
Just to give you an example of how that can happen, even in this modern day and age, there's a famous monk in Sri Lanka, at least he's famous in Sri Lanka,

50
00:07:21,295 --> 00:07:25,119
He's a Danish monk and he lives out in the forests.

51
00:07:25,139 --> 00:07:29,024
And he lives in what is a three-sided kuti.

52
00:07:29,043 --> 00:07:31,266
So there's only three sides to his hut with a roof.

53
00:07:32,228 --> 00:07:39,235
So that means that he lives quite happily with snakes, poisonous creatures, poisonous spiders and things like that.

54
00:07:40,117 --> 00:07:42,139
And that's his life as an ascetic life.

55
00:07:42,180 --> 00:07:45,142
There's two or three of them now that live like that up there.

56
00:07:47,603 --> 00:07:52,033
and he would wander down to the local village for his food.

57
00:07:52,714 --> 00:08:04,482
And on one occasion when he came back, an elephant jumped out, and he told me he didn't have time to chant the loving-kinder sutta, and the elephant ran over him.

58
00:08:05,254 --> 00:08:16,069
Unfortunately, he stood on his hip and broke his hip, and he lay there all day, all night, until the villagers thought, why hasn't he arrived?

59
00:08:16,108 --> 00:08:18,211
So they went off looking for him and found him on the path.

60
00:08:19,973 --> 00:08:22,697
Now, the fact is that that elephant did not mean to kill him.

61
00:08:23,317 --> 00:08:26,983
They tell you if an elephant means to kill you, it will definitely kill you.

62
00:08:28,345 --> 00:08:30,908
The elephant, it seems, only came out to give him a little shock.

63
00:08:31,663 --> 00:08:35,691
But unfortunately, in so doing, went and stood on him and broke his hip.

64
00:08:37,634 --> 00:08:40,780
So I can't remember the name of the monk.

65
00:08:40,801 --> 00:08:51,961
So he ended up in hospital, and he told me that they did a terrible job on his hip, and he still goes around with one leg half up in the air.

66
00:08:54,044 --> 00:08:55,106
But...

67
00:08:56,182 --> 00:09:05,072
This story filtered down to Colombo, which is about, I suppose, maybe at the most 80, 100 miles away.

68
00:09:06,394 --> 00:09:10,818
And I was visiting Colombo at the time, and there was a Swedish monk there.

69
00:09:11,480 --> 00:09:13,322
And he said to me, have you heard about so-and-so?

70
00:09:14,022 --> 00:09:15,163
And I said, I have.

71
00:09:15,264 --> 00:09:17,004
By then, I'd only heard rumors, you know.

72
00:09:18,126 --> 00:09:18,846
I said, yeah.

73
00:09:18,927 --> 00:09:20,208
I said, this thing about an elephant.

74
00:09:20,328 --> 00:09:21,190
He said, oh, yeah.

75
00:09:21,210 --> 00:09:23,052
He says, quite remarkable, he said.

76
00:09:24,381 --> 00:09:44,500
He was sitting in posture under a tree in meditation and a big she-elephant with a little child came along and they were entranced by him and the little baby elephant moved towards him and tried to sit in posture, fell over and broke his hip.

77
00:09:47,634 --> 00:09:52,340
So this happens within a couple of months, 100 miles distance.

78
00:09:52,400 --> 00:10:01,870
So this gives you an idea of how apocryphal stories gather around somebody who has a certain reputation about them.

79
00:10:03,552 --> 00:10:16,207
But for our purposes, the stories are just there really to enhance the basic template, which is the path that we're on, that's all.

80
00:10:20,052 --> 00:10:27,837
So in the story, of course, the Buddha doesn't begin with the life that he's born into.

81
00:10:27,898 --> 00:10:30,687
He's been through these thousands of rebirths.

82
00:10:31,644 --> 00:10:37,938
And there's a point when he is an ascetic called Sumeda.

83
00:10:38,701 --> 00:10:50,768
Now, you won't be surprised to know that Sumeda was, in fact, a very rich prince who gave everything up when he saw the vanity of life and ended up taking on the ascetic life.

84
00:10:53,717 --> 00:11:00,466
He heard about the Buddha, and having heard the name of the Buddha, was greatly moved by it.

85
00:11:00,706 --> 00:11:02,388
So he went to meet Dipankara.

86
00:11:03,769 --> 00:11:07,433
And when Dipankara came, there was a puddle of water.

87
00:11:07,615 --> 00:11:08,556
I'm sure you know the story.

88
00:11:09,177 --> 00:11:20,350
And he threw his cloak upon the puddle and threw himself down upon the cloak and asked that Dipankara, the Buddha, and all the Arahats who were following him should use his body as a stepping stone.

89
00:11:21,899 --> 00:11:31,952
And when Dipankara saw this and saw the qualities of Sumedha, he prophesied that this person would indeed become a future Buddha.

90
00:11:33,674 --> 00:11:41,465
So now, you see, we have to consider, is there anybody you know that you would do that to?

91
00:11:42,807 --> 00:11:48,615
Throw your coat down, lie in front of them and say, please use my body as a stepping stone?

92
00:11:49,793 --> 00:12:00,927
So it brings up this whole relationship that we might have to a teacher and how we relate to the teacher in our spiritual lives.

93
00:12:02,551 --> 00:12:08,278
So one of the two things that come to mind are around this word authority.

94
00:12:10,140 --> 00:12:17,150
So we say somebody is an authority and we also say somebody is in authority over authority.

95
00:12:17,840 --> 00:12:21,326
And these two things are very different relationships, aren't they?

96
00:12:21,346 --> 00:12:31,466
So when somebody is in authority over you, it inspires fear, a certain anxiety, because they have power over your life.

97
00:12:32,469 --> 00:12:39,222
But an authority is somebody who obviously you respect, and that brings up in you a certain sense of reverence.

98
00:12:40,687 --> 00:12:45,254
However, that split is not so, shall we say, easy.

99
00:12:45,654 --> 00:12:53,044
You can't just say, well, I look upon the Buddha as an authority, but he definitely doesn't have any authority over me.

100
00:12:54,567 --> 00:13:02,499
There is that, shall we say, point where having respect for somebody, you therefore accept their teachings.

101
00:13:03,179 --> 00:13:10,509
You, as it were, surrender to what the person says or what the person is asking us to do.

102
00:13:11,164 --> 00:13:24,663
So even these days when we're very sceptical of doctors, once we've, shall we say, had faith in the doctor, once the doctor has prescribed a certain thing, we tend to follow the prescription.

103
00:13:25,565 --> 00:13:38,943
So when we're thinking about our relationship to the Buddha, and indeed to any teacher, there is that reflection to be had as to what my relationship is to this person.

104
00:13:40,155 --> 00:13:49,190
At one end, of course, you've got the sort of fawning devotee, the one who goes around kissing the teacher's feet, and whatever the teacher says must be true.

105
00:13:50,272 --> 00:13:53,756
So this isn't quite what the Buddha would have wanted, I think.

106
00:13:54,639 --> 00:13:58,924
He wants a person to maintain a certain independence.

107
00:14:00,287 --> 00:14:07,698
And if you remember, I think it was just before he died, wasn't it, there was a young monk looking upon him with great admiration,

108
00:14:08,455 --> 00:14:13,166
while he was there, and he sent him packing off, packed him off to the forest, didn't he?

109
00:14:13,186 --> 00:14:23,510
He didn't particularly want to be surrounded by people with adoring eyes.

110
00:14:25,211 --> 00:14:38,686
And yet the other end, of course, is the continual sceptical follower who doesn't believe a word you say and who won't actually do what you want them to do.

111
00:14:39,767 --> 00:14:44,152
So those of you who have been teachers, I know they must have come across these two types of people.

112
00:14:45,113 --> 00:14:54,982
So it's a case of, again, recognising that the Dharma that we have is spoken, is passed on to us by another human being

113
00:14:55,755 --> 00:15:01,782
And it has that quality of having been lived, having been experienced.

114
00:15:01,802 --> 00:15:15,634
So sometimes reflecting upon that, reflecting upon the personage or the person of the Buddha, brings about that sense of reverence, that sense of right attitude to the teaching.

115
00:15:21,039 --> 00:15:22,741
Then of course there's...

116
00:15:24,476 --> 00:15:30,404
the whole business of relationships even to our teachers here and now, you know, who we listen to.

117
00:15:30,424 --> 00:15:48,190
And that sort of ability to receive and yet not to lose one's own independence, as it were, to receive and to have that attitude of trial and error to make sure that

118
00:15:48,557 --> 00:15:58,998
There isn't just that blind acceptance, a sort of blind faith to what's being said or to what we're being asked to do.

119
00:15:59,057 --> 00:16:06,712
So all these things are important in our spiritual life, you see, just to get the attitude right.

120
00:16:08,436 --> 00:16:10,600
And these attitudes, remember, are...

121
00:16:12,131 --> 00:16:13,374
beneath our practice.

122
00:16:13,433 --> 00:16:21,624
They're there as certain traits that are subconscious, or should we say subliminal to our practice.

123
00:16:21,644 --> 00:16:34,360
And so if you find yourself, for instance, always balking and always not wanting to do things, you know, sometimes ask yourself, what is your basic attitude to the Dharma?

124
00:16:35,216 --> 00:16:37,779
So here we come to this whole business of bowing, you see.

125
00:16:38,301 --> 00:16:42,005
So bowing for Westerners is a bit of a pain, really.

126
00:16:43,908 --> 00:16:51,357
I remember when I first went to my first classes in Zen, and there they only bow from the waist, of course, you know.

127
00:16:52,418 --> 00:16:56,163
And everybody did it, so I mean, I did it, but I thought, oh, this is ridiculous.

128
00:16:57,424 --> 00:17:01,090
And it took me quite a long time to get the hang of what bowing was about, actually.

129
00:17:02,216 --> 00:17:02,857
I mean, I did it.

130
00:17:02,898 --> 00:17:05,560
You do it because, well, because he's doing it, you know.

131
00:17:06,342 --> 00:17:10,507
And in the Zen practice, of course, you bow even to the room you're leaving.

132
00:17:10,647 --> 00:17:11,648
You bow to your cushion.

133
00:17:11,949 --> 00:17:12,910
You bow to your plate.

134
00:17:13,009 --> 00:17:14,051
You bow to your toilet.

135
00:17:14,673 --> 00:17:15,973
There's nothing you don't bow to, you see.

136
00:17:17,256 --> 00:17:21,381
So in the end, you get the feeling that there may be something in this bowing.

137
00:17:22,863 --> 00:17:28,630
And bowing is just a strong body language, isn't it, for surrender, for that.

138
00:17:28,980 --> 00:17:34,882
That ability just to receive without negativity, without aversion.

139
00:17:37,191 --> 00:17:41,184
And that connection between the mind and the body.

140
00:17:42,058 --> 00:17:49,971
Remember that the Eightfold Path always begins with right understanding, then right attitude, and then right speech, right action, right livelihood.

141
00:17:50,291 --> 00:17:55,540
So somehow the right understanding and the right attitude needs to be expressed in a certain way.

142
00:17:56,721 --> 00:18:07,779
So when you feel a resistance, when you feel a resistance against the practice, some form that you don't want to do it, you can't do it, something like that,

143
00:18:08,636 --> 00:18:18,474
Bow, you know, just actually try it, just actually, just secretly in your room, you don't have to do it as a public display, you know.

144
00:18:19,256 --> 00:18:27,289
And to actually bow and to, when the body is in that posture, it's in that posture of surrender, see.

145
00:18:27,309 --> 00:18:33,260
It's ready to be trod upon and to be used by a higher being as a stepping stone.

146
00:18:34,337 --> 00:18:38,085
So that brings about that sense of humility.

147
00:18:38,766 --> 00:18:47,320
And in there, that feeling of reverence.

148
00:18:50,486 --> 00:18:53,612
I was going to say the word obedience, but that's a horrible word for us.

149
00:18:54,313 --> 00:18:55,434
We don't want to be obedient.

150
00:18:57,085 --> 00:19:07,415
So these little stories, you see, when you read about them about the Buddha, if you just let your mind wander about it and just ask yourself, what's its meaning for me?

151
00:19:07,655 --> 00:19:11,480
How does it relate to me personally?

152
00:19:12,119 --> 00:19:15,364
How can it inform my own practice?

153
00:19:16,744 --> 00:19:21,450
And in that way, this archetype, this exemplar is imbibed.

154
00:19:21,789 --> 00:19:23,531
It becomes part of our own nature.

155
00:19:28,742 --> 00:19:33,392
The next thing of course is the whole teaching around these rebirths.

156
00:19:35,296 --> 00:19:42,651
And at some later date maybe I'll go into the idea of rebirth.

157
00:19:43,491 --> 00:19:52,884
What always interests me is this underlying conception of time, how we relate to time itself.

158
00:19:52,904 --> 00:19:57,811
So in the Buddha's time, the idea was that time was circular.

159
00:19:58,112 --> 00:20:00,214
It was constantly repeating itself.

160
00:20:01,817 --> 00:20:07,945
And I think if you just look at just an ordinary year, then you can see how that can be understood.

161
00:20:08,026 --> 00:20:10,308
I mean, it's the seasons.

162
00:20:10,643 --> 00:20:16,713
And every day the sun rises and it sets and you get up and you go to bed and you're born and you die.

163
00:20:16,753 --> 00:20:34,727
And so there's that feeling that, in fact, although everything is, shall we say, a little bit different, the underlying blueprint, the underlying motion is one of constant circularity, constantly going round and round and round.

164
00:20:36,039 --> 00:20:52,429
And if you can just imagine now, if you really believe that, just for one moment put yourself into that mental state of believing that you've lived a life over and over and over again.

165
00:20:52,847 --> 00:20:55,571
Sometimes there's a horse or an elephant.

166
00:20:56,011 --> 00:20:59,896
Sometimes there's a little being, a mouse, and then a human being.

167
00:21:00,077 --> 00:21:04,002
But always you just keep coming back, keep coming back.

168
00:21:04,163 --> 00:21:09,891
And it's always birth, old age, sickness, death, a bit of happiness stuck in there somewhere.

169
00:21:10,811 --> 00:21:18,923
But this never-ending, ceaseless movement of just going round and round, the same old thing, the same old job,

170
00:21:18,903 --> 00:21:29,593
The same old relationships, the same old fallouts, and the same old making it up, and the same old breakfast, and the same old toilet.

171
00:21:30,153 --> 00:21:32,174
It's always the same, going round and round.

172
00:21:32,654 --> 00:21:38,740
And you get that feeling, maybe, of that growing despair of how the hell do you get off this wheel?

173
00:21:40,362 --> 00:21:48,690
So if you have an image, shall we say, of a roundabout, and you've got your horse, and you're going round and round, and having a good time, and the beer and all that,

174
00:21:49,462 --> 00:22:00,574
And then suddenly, you know, the leg falls off your horse and you've got to get off and put it back on and things fall off and arguments start and people start throwing bottles about and you think, I want to get off.

175
00:22:01,954 --> 00:22:05,898
And then when you want to get off this roundabout, all you see around you is this void.

176
00:22:08,261 --> 00:22:11,664
Whether you look down or up or across, there's just nothing there.

177
00:22:12,286 --> 00:22:15,127
You're just stuck on this roundabout and there's no way off it.

178
00:22:15,888 --> 00:22:18,811
And if you were to jump, then you just get sucked back into it.

179
00:22:19,416 --> 00:22:31,430
So if you can sort of imagine that sort of mentality, that was the mentality around the Buddha's time of circularity, of constant repetition, of no escape.

180
00:22:32,151 --> 00:22:36,615
And so the idea of escaping this was one of the obsessions of the time.

181
00:22:36,655 --> 00:22:41,141
How do you stop this rebirthing?

182
00:22:41,821 --> 00:22:44,044
So there were many answers, of course.

183
00:22:44,124 --> 00:22:46,707
There were some who believed in...

184
00:22:47,092 --> 00:22:50,218
even at the end of this life, you completely annihilated and that was it.

185
00:22:51,179 --> 00:22:56,828
And that the best bet would be to make the best of this life as you can and really go for it.

186
00:22:57,631 --> 00:23:01,377
So that sort of thought is well known to us these days.

187
00:23:02,439 --> 00:23:06,686
And there were some who thought that you went on for a few rebirths and then you...

188
00:23:06,952 --> 00:23:09,316
you're annihilated after that.

189
00:23:10,237 --> 00:23:14,602
And then there were some who thought, well, you did carry on rebirthing, but it got better.

190
00:23:15,202 --> 00:23:18,467
And you ended up being a great Brahma up in the high heavens.

191
00:23:20,589 --> 00:23:25,776
These things, of course, the Buddha would have known.

192
00:23:26,057 --> 00:23:30,362
He would have known all these arguments, all these ideas.

193
00:23:30,696 --> 00:23:42,362
And even so, as you know, through his practice, he came to realize that no matter what beautiful state of mind he could attain, it didn't last.

194
00:23:42,462 --> 00:23:49,498
There was still that falling off, that particular level of being, you might say.

195
00:23:50,980 --> 00:24:02,692
Now, as opposed to that, these days, you see, and that's why we find it difficult, perhaps, to accept this idea of rebirthing and whatnot, is that our idea of time is an arrow.

196
00:24:03,053 --> 00:24:04,535
We actually think we're going somewhere.

197
00:24:05,175 --> 00:24:06,877
We have this idea of progress.

198
00:24:07,218 --> 00:24:09,059
We're going from this place to that place.

199
00:24:10,741 --> 00:24:17,088
This is embedded, really, deep within the Judaic Christian religion, but especially in Christianity.

200
00:24:17,170 --> 00:24:23,685
where the early Christians for many years presumed that the second coming was about to happen.

201
00:24:24,688 --> 00:24:33,609
And the idea of the medieval society was to establish something stable, something which was godlike, ready for this second coming.

202
00:24:34,535 --> 00:24:47,565
As the centuries rolled on, and it didn't quite seem that it was going to happen, there came the idea started off by a monk, writing at the time, who talked about three ages.

203
00:24:47,865 --> 00:25:02,462
The age of the Father, which was the age before Christ, the age of the Son, which was the age that we're living in, and the age of the Spirit, which would come in some future time when the human race had progressed to receive it.

204
00:25:02,963 --> 00:25:10,333
So there came this idea of progression, the idea that we were going somewhere, the human race was actually going somewhere.

205
00:25:11,554 --> 00:25:15,679
And this has been accentuated in our day and time by technology.

206
00:25:16,502 --> 00:25:19,387
It would be foolish to say that technology has not progressed.

207
00:25:20,249 --> 00:25:27,520
And we get the impression that just because we have this enormous progression in technology, therefore we must be going somewhere.

208
00:25:28,843 --> 00:25:39,000
But unfortunately, when we look around us and see what we're doing with this technology, then that hope begins to fizzle and fade.

209
00:25:39,992 --> 00:25:47,101
But even so, we're stuck on this idea that this progress, that we're actually moving towards some sort of aim.

210
00:25:48,721 --> 00:26:04,278
And when we bring that to the Buddha's teaching, then we find the idea of rebirth and whatnot difficult to accept because we've lost that sense of circularity of time, that constant repetition, the repetitiousness of time within time.

211
00:26:06,537 --> 00:26:13,384
And this idea of progress, of course, seeps into our practice.

212
00:26:13,403 --> 00:26:15,605
So there is that quality.

213
00:26:15,646 --> 00:26:26,438
It's not as though Easterners don't have a sense of, say, people who live still with that sense of circularity, which is, I would say, most Easterners.

214
00:26:27,439 --> 00:26:34,266
It's not as though they're not grasping in their practice, but in a sense it's coming from a slightly more superficial level.

215
00:26:34,769 --> 00:26:43,116
Within us, I think, we have a much deeper level that we think that there's some sort of progress to be had through the practice.

216
00:26:43,416 --> 00:26:50,624
And what it does is it seeps into our practice as a sense of trying to do something.

217
00:26:51,505 --> 00:26:52,746
Trying to do something.

218
00:26:52,786 --> 00:26:56,289
So we've been able to do a lot with our technology.

219
00:26:56,690 --> 00:27:04,017
So when we come to sit, there's that underlying, I think, understanding or presumption that we can do something.

220
00:27:04,654 --> 00:27:10,444
And the idea that actually we don't have to do anything but just watch is difficult for us.

221
00:27:12,607 --> 00:27:27,873
Sometimes, you know, when I was in the East, and especially in the villages, I didn't go out very often, but especially in the villages, it always seemed to me quite remarkable how people could just sit and seemingly stare.

222
00:27:29,195 --> 00:27:31,219
They would just stare at things.

223
00:27:31,351 --> 00:27:36,196
whether it was a fly going around a window or just the countryside.

224
00:27:37,519 --> 00:27:43,846
But when you looked into their face, it wasn't as though the face was dead, but they were just able just to stare.

225
00:27:44,969 --> 00:27:56,303
And that ability of just to relax into the present moment and just to be in it without wanting anything from it at all, but just to be completely receptive, you see.

226
00:27:57,124 --> 00:27:59,146
So we find that, I think, a little difficult.

227
00:27:59,566 --> 00:28:12,220
And I'm suggesting that maybe it's to do with our conception of time at a deeper level, the idea of progress, that we've made progress, and that it's up to us to do something.

228
00:28:13,560 --> 00:28:26,535
And the idea that the whole process of purification of the heart and of insight comes by actually a process of relaxing and just watching,

229
00:28:27,442 --> 00:28:42,105
and everything arises quite naturally, is, I think, just a little bit difficult for us, that's all.

230
00:28:42,125 --> 00:28:54,784
With these two types of time, you see, the circular time and this arrow, the time as an arrow, there's another time, and this time we can call the immediate presence.

231
00:28:55,557 --> 00:29:04,648
In Christian mysticism, they talk of the nunc stans and the nunc fluens.

232
00:29:06,692 --> 00:29:11,679
So there's a now which is in a state of flow and a now which is absolutely still.

233
00:29:14,041 --> 00:29:23,775
Perhaps you've had the impression sometimes, I'm sure you've had it on a train where there's another train by next to yours,

234
00:29:23,906 --> 00:29:28,153
And when one of them moves, you don't know whether you're moving or whether the other tray is moving.

235
00:29:28,193 --> 00:29:32,560
It just takes that little bit, that little moment to gather the fact that either you are moving or you're not.

236
00:29:34,483 --> 00:29:50,167
You might have got the sense sometimes, driving, especially driving, just driving down a motorway, for instance, of instead of you passing through that space, that you were still and the space was passing through you.

237
00:29:51,193 --> 00:29:57,660
It's something you can try anyway, so it's only another way of, as we say, positioning yourself.

238
00:29:57,680 --> 00:30:10,451
So suddenly to find within yourself that position where there is that stillness and everything that is arising within our perceptual faculties is what's moving.

239
00:30:12,134 --> 00:30:17,538
Now that presents us with a different idea of time because...

240
00:30:18,548 --> 00:30:47,256
the idea of circular time and the idea of time moving as an arrow demands that we go with it demands that we are part of that motion so now when we sit in meditation and we gain that position at least of the observer see being aware of transience being aware of things arising and passing away means that that which is aware of it can't itself be arising and passing away

241
00:30:48,281 --> 00:30:54,190
And it's sitting in that position which gives us a different feel for time.

242
00:30:55,751 --> 00:31:01,920
It's not that time isn't circular or that there isn't some sort of movement.

243
00:31:02,661 --> 00:31:04,523
For instance, you can't go back on time.

244
00:31:05,505 --> 00:31:14,356
But the fact is that in terms of the actual experience of being in time is only momentary.

245
00:31:15,181 --> 00:31:21,988
So this idea of time is just a way that the mind relates the way things have happened in the past.

246
00:31:23,568 --> 00:31:26,192
When we talk about space, what do we mean?

247
00:31:26,511 --> 00:31:29,355
We mean simply the relationship of objects, don't we?

248
00:31:31,057 --> 00:31:35,060
It's the way all that space is, is a measurement between objects.

249
00:31:35,942 --> 00:31:39,905
If there were no objects, there couldn't really be any space.

250
00:31:41,252 --> 00:31:42,275
So it's with time.

251
00:31:42,375 --> 00:31:44,358
If there were no events, there'd be no time.

252
00:31:45,099 --> 00:31:57,083
And our concept of time, circular or arrow, is dependent on how we, the mind, that's it, this particular consciousness, organizes events.

253
00:31:59,528 --> 00:32:02,933
So all memory is past.

254
00:32:03,134 --> 00:32:04,576
You can't go back on memory.

255
00:32:05,231 --> 00:32:05,752
That's it.

256
00:32:05,772 --> 00:32:06,292
It's finished.

257
00:32:06,713 --> 00:32:07,974
And the future hasn't happened.

258
00:32:08,675 --> 00:32:14,663
So by remembering that, all these concepts that we have of time are simply mind-made.

259
00:32:15,463 --> 00:32:27,038
And that if we can find this position within ourselves of observing events arising and passing away, then we find this other position where there's no time.

260
00:32:33,785 --> 00:32:51,125
The other thing that comes up with the idea of rebirth and these constant, such a long time that it takes to become an enlightened being is the question of why it takes so long.

261
00:32:52,386 --> 00:33:02,137
Why is it that once we've sort of grasped the teaching, the anicca dukanata, everything arises and passes away, we cause our own suffering and there is no self anymore.

262
00:33:02,708 --> 00:33:05,192
Why isn't that enough?

263
00:33:05,751 --> 00:33:12,541
Why isn't that enough for us to move forward rapidly and find ourselves in a week or two fully liberated?

264
00:33:12,561 --> 00:33:23,117
I remember a friend of mine who, when he first heard about Buddhist teaching and Nibbana and all that, he decided to do a course.

265
00:33:23,898 --> 00:33:32,090
And if you think about it, when you go on a course, at the end of the course, you achieve what you get, what you went in for, and you get a certificate.

266
00:33:32,981 --> 00:33:38,509
So he presumed that by the end of the week he'd have grasped this idea of nirvana and he'd be away.

267
00:33:39,692 --> 00:33:46,843
And he told me, as the week wore on and the time came for him to leave, there was this growing sense of despair and disappointment.

268
00:33:48,925 --> 00:33:51,990
Later on he was able to overcome that, of course, and continued his practice.

269
00:33:52,892 --> 00:34:01,285
But the fact that we have this idea or this hope

270
00:34:01,450 --> 00:34:08,123
that things might progress very quickly, is undermined by our practice.

271
00:34:08,503 --> 00:34:10,849
We find it hard, we find it difficult.

272
00:34:11,811 --> 00:34:21,130
And surely the reason is that our conditioning is so deeply ingrained and we keep falling back.

273
00:34:21,295 --> 00:34:26,126
Every time we progress a little bit, we then fall back a bit.

274
00:34:26,326 --> 00:34:35,186
So here we're working very hard for a couple of weeks, a month, a whole year, and then we go out, and before we know it, we slip back into the old ways.

275
00:34:36,007 --> 00:34:38,172
And so all the old conditioning gets lighted up again.

276
00:34:39,250 --> 00:34:53,068
So it's a case of recognising that it's going to take quite a time to develop enough momentum to keep moving forward at a pace which seems to us obvious.

277
00:34:54,251 --> 00:35:02,041
Often you can only really look back over a good space of time, maybe five, ten years, and say, oh yes, I have progressed.

278
00:35:02,882 --> 00:35:05,246
But if you look back over a week, it does seem appalling.

279
00:35:05,766 --> 00:35:08,110
I put all this work in and we don't seem to be getting very far.

280
00:35:09,152 --> 00:35:17,041
So it's a case of, again, that sense of, you know, realism, really, a sort of humility about ourselves.

281
00:35:18,143 --> 00:35:27,492
There was a very famous Hindu saint in Sri Lanka whose saying was, the spiritual life was one step forward, two steps back.

282
00:35:27,994 --> 00:35:32,818
So you can see it's even, in all traditions, it's understood to be difficult.

283
00:35:33,760 --> 00:35:39,126
And it's a case of building up these paramis, these

284
00:35:39,864 --> 00:35:45,672
these virtues within us, and that takes time.

285
00:35:51,842 --> 00:36:07,003
The other question, of course, when we go back to this archetype and exemplar, is the fact that there must be something in us which already knows that it needs to seek liberation.

286
00:36:08,349 --> 00:36:34,947
These stories which talk about eons and eons and eons and going back to Deepankara many world systems ago, from an archetypal point of view, is suggesting that within us, at all times, there has been that seed that wants to find out its own true nature.

287
00:36:36,159 --> 00:36:43,469
When Buddhism developed through the Mahayana, of course, it became known as the embryo of the Buddha.

288
00:36:43,838 --> 00:36:52,588
And the embryo of the Buddha, through the practice, through these constant rebirths, finally becomes the Tathagata.

289
00:36:53,489 --> 00:36:58,574
The Tathagata Garbha, the embryo of the Tathagata, becomes the Tathagata.

290
00:36:59,215 --> 00:37:12,411
So the idea that there is something in us which is seeking liberation is presumed within the practice.

291
00:37:13,606 --> 00:37:20,038
And this, of course, is in the Buddha's own life, in his growing dissatisfaction with the way he was living.

292
00:37:24,065 --> 00:37:34,686
So, in a sense, whether the Buddha had arisen or not, you see, we would have been seeking, we would have been, in our own way, seeking our own liberation.

293
00:37:39,103 --> 00:37:44,952
So that then now brings us to his descent into his mother's womb.

294
00:37:46,193 --> 00:37:52,182
And I wonder if I might not have too much time to do this.

295
00:37:53,083 --> 00:37:59,052
I suppose the last...

296
00:38:00,130 --> 00:38:09,880
The last thing to say before I go on to, because this will take two or three talks to finally get through his life and just see what we can glean from it, you know.

297
00:38:13,324 --> 00:38:18,329
Just to go back on the whole idea of the Buddha being an archetype and an exemplar.

298
00:38:20,251 --> 00:38:26,356
The idea that he was an actual human being and that we as human beings therefore

299
00:38:26,893 --> 00:38:37,809
have the same capacity to attain exactly what he attained and how that rises in us, that inner faith and confidence about our own practice.

300
00:38:37,829 --> 00:38:44,539
So when you have doubts about yourself, you know, everybody else can do it, but I can't.

301
00:38:44,659 --> 00:38:45,641
I'm special that way.

302
00:38:46,121 --> 00:38:53,492
So remind yourself that, in fact, the capability of becoming fully liberated is there within you.

303
00:38:54,585 --> 00:38:59,032
And to ponder that, to ponder that, to really sit within that inner confidence.

304
00:39:00,614 --> 00:39:22,347
The idea of a relationship that we have towards a teacher as an authority or in authority and how those two can become confused and how we must maintain that certain distance within ourselves, that certain capacity to constantly reflect upon our practice and make sure that we know what we're doing, you know.

305
00:39:25,871 --> 00:39:34,045
The idea that of time, time being only a figment of the imagination, it's only the way that we look at things, experience things.

306
00:39:34,625 --> 00:39:41,836
And that if we can, as it were, stand outside the process, which is exactly what we're doing when we're sitting, standing outside the process.

307
00:39:42,336 --> 00:39:49,347
Remember that everything is being created by our own minds, even though the world out there has some reality.

308
00:39:49,918 --> 00:39:54,768
The reality that we experience is only being created by our own minds.

309
00:39:55,289 --> 00:40:08,396
So to be able to sit back and take that position within ourselves and to watch our minds and to watch the flow of events within our minds immediately pulls us out of this idea that time is circular or that it's going anywhere.

310
00:40:09,840 --> 00:40:11,083
That is another position.

311
00:40:13,797 --> 00:40:22,592
And to have the patience, you know, to work with it, not to presume that things are going to happen too quickly, you know.

312
00:40:26,418 --> 00:40:35,112
So I hope my words have been of some assistance and that before very long you will join the Arahats and become fully liberated.

